<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-887-946  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 887 946.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Oct 25 1989 n118 p33(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business and Computer Publications1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>White paper demands jail for hackers. (study by the English LawCommission)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United KingdomComputer HackersComputer CrimesLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>White paper demans jail for hackers After a year-long study of computercrimes, the English Law Commission has issued a white paper on criminal lawand computer misuse.andP;  This is available from Her Majesty's Stationery Officeat 5.60 pounds sterling.andM;The white paper follows the issue of a green discussion paper late last year,and a similar white paper from the Scottish Law Commission, also issued latelast year.andM;The proposals, which look likely to become legislation in the nextParliamentary session, recommend punishing proven computer hackers withprison sentences of a maximum of five years.andM;In addition the white paper, which will be presented to Parliament afterrecommendations from the Department of Trade and Industry, calls for thecreation of three new criminal offences to try and combat attempts by hackersto infiltrate computer systems and interfere with the internal programming ofthe machines.andM;Announcing the white paper, Law Commissioner Richard Buston, QC, said thatthe new laws would apply &quot;only to a person who knows he is unauthorized, nota careless person who just presses a wrong button or makes a mistake&quot;andM;He called such computer attacks &quot;particularly serious if they are directedagainst computers which are now used to perform many industrial andcommercial operations&quot;.andP;  Buxton added that such activities are not now&quot;properly covered by the criminal law&quot;.andM;If the Law Commission proposals are accepted, the Government will create abasic offense of &quot;unauthorized entry into a computer system,&quot; which wouldbring a possible three-month prison term for anyone convicted under the newlaw.andM;The proposals also include stronger provisions that will deal with seriouscomputer vandals, Buxton said.andM;Under the plan, an offence of &quot;unauthorized entry into a computer system withintent to commit, or to assist the commission of, a serious crime&quot; would becreated as well as a third offence which would comprise &quot;alteringcomputer-held data or programs&quot;.andM;Both crimes would be punishable by a five-year jail term.andM;The third offence is perhaps the most interesting, since the white papereffectively recommends that the deliberate creation or passing on of a virusprogram should be punished by a prison sentence of a maximum five years.andO;</TEXT></DOC>